    <item>
      <title>15.02 The Story of the Villainess</title>
      <link>https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-02-the-story-of-the-villainess/</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-02-the-story-of-the-villainess/</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 27 Aug 2025 12:33:25 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;main class="wp-block-group is-layout-flow wp-block-group-is-layout-flow"&gt; &lt;div class="wp-block-group is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"&gt;&lt;h1 class="wp-block-post-title"&gt;15.02 The Story of the&amp;nbsp;Villainess&lt;/h1&gt;   &lt;div style="height:1px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;   &lt;/div&gt;   &lt;div class="entry-content wp-block-post-content is-layout-constrained wp-block-post-content-is-layout-constrained"&gt; &lt;p&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-01-older-brothers-care/"&gt;Previous Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chou’u was initially a surviving member of the Shi clan.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;These individuals were originally not allowed to live, but Jinshi said he had made a promise to overlook the crimes of those who have died once.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Who did he make such a promise to?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao recalled the girl who loved insects.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;That being said, the children’s families have all been executed. The reason the surviving members of the Shi clan were raised in secrecy. This would prevent the emperor&amp;#8217;s sentencing from being perceived as lenient and keep the children under surveillance, so they would not contemplate avenging their parents.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Chou’u was the only one among the children who lost his memories as a side effect of the resurrection drug. Half his body was also paralysed.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was for that reason Chou’u was the only one living separately in the pleasure district.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao opened the book she borrowed from Zilin. “The villainess of the north, huh?” she said, flipping through the pages.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was a story common on the streets about &lt;em&gt;Loulan&lt;/em&gt;, the villainess of the north.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The story was about a former consort abandoned by the late emperor who had controlled her daughter and attempted to bring down the country.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;The general idea isn’t wrong.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;However, the villainess &lt;em&gt;Loulan&lt;/em&gt;’s depiction and lines just felt wrong. No, perhaps Maomao just didn’t know this &lt;em&gt;Loulan&lt;/em&gt;: a haughty and domineering consort from the book? It seems the writing had greatly exaggerated the rumours.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was written that the late emperor did not pick &lt;em&gt;Shenmei&lt;/em&gt;—&lt;em&gt;Loulan&lt;/em&gt;’s mother—to sleep with, having discovered her true nature. Setting &lt;em&gt;Shenmei&lt;/em&gt;’s personality aside, the real reason was different. It seemed to her the late emperor have been romanticised to some extent as well.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The contents might have been written with censors in mind, seeing how real names were used.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;People would normally get angry when their friends get depicted in a bad light.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;However, that was the kind of performance &lt;em&gt;Loulan &lt;/em&gt;enacted. On the contrary, the more of a villain &lt;em&gt;Loulan &lt;/em&gt;was in the story, the more it felt like her intentions had been reached. If anything, &lt;em&gt;Loulan &lt;/em&gt;would be pleased if she were to know about it.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Shenmei &lt;/em&gt;was more the hopeless villain to Maomao, but &lt;em&gt;Loulan &lt;/em&gt;was the one fully treated as the villain in both rumours and this book.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;At the end of the scuffle, she injured the imperial brother’s face.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Only this part is clearly fictional.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As she had injured the face as beautiful as a celestial maiden, it made her the most evil woman of all. The reason being that he was the most beautiful was clichéd too.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;With all that said, it had to be a worthwhile read, seeing how it had been passed around and read to the point of getting dirty. Maomao would probably find it interesting if she were an unrelated party.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao closed the book, changed out of her dirty clothes from working in the fields, then headed over to Verdigris Mansion.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;The brothel was getting ready for opening, so the women were moving about busily.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao called out to Sazen who was closing up shop. “Where’s Chou’u?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“He went home just before,” he answered.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“No, after that.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Sazen seemed to have noticed something from Maomao’s expression. “Did something happen?” he asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“&amp;#8230;Is this book popular?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Sazen’s face darkened. He was one of the people who knew of Chou’u’s situation. “Shall we talk while I close up?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Sure.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao and Sazen went inside the apothecary. The inside was cluttered as he had been in the middle of tidying up.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;He makes medicine conscientiously.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;While he lacked creativity, he diligently kept to what he had been taught. It was both Sazen’s strong and weak point. As things were done the same way, Maomao helped with cleaning up.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Did Chou’u get his memory back?&amp;#8221; Maomao asked as she checked the medicine left on the shelf.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I’ve no idea about that. Just that he normally hates studying and yet this book alone he’s read completely.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It would be troubling if he recovered his memory. The special treatment was taken on the assumption that he had no memories. You could even call it an act of kindness.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“There’s no way he’d answer simply if you press him, yeah. Is he rebellious against you too, Sazen?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“He’s not that strong against me. But he’s at a difficult age and I’m afraid he’ll soon surpass me in height and I’ll lose to him.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You won’t lose.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Even if he grew taller, he would still have his paralysis.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“I’ll also ask Ukyou to have Chou’u’s monitoring strengthened, would that be fine?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Don’t ask me. Above anything else, if he does anything strange, I’ll report it immediately, so—”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“So?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Don’t make Chou’u the enemy of the emperor.” Sazen peeked at Maomao’s expression. Chou’u may be a cheeky brat, but Sazen had some degree of fondness for the child.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Even Maomao thought that simply disposing of him would be irresponsible. “Spare me from such a bothersome thing. Above all, that would break the promise.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“The promise? I see,” Sazen said in a curiously understanding tone.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao didn’t think she told Sazen who that promise was made with, but it sounded like he was pretending to know. She decided to let it go, thinking that he must have heard it in passing.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Next, can I talk about what’s bothering me about this book?” he asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“What about it?” she said.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Sazen flipped through the book. “The author wrote this for the mass market, right?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, it’s just like the rumours.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But this right here.” He pointed to a certain description.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;It was written that the many tortures ordered by Loulan made her a villainess.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“But it was her mother who did the torturing… hm?” Maomao tilted her head.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“See, isn’t it strange?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s strange.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;All of Shenmei’s deeds had become Loulan’s.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Actually, all of the tortures were done inside the fortress.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Really?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“You probably wouldn&amp;#8217;t know, but the details about the fortress are strangely consistent too.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“So you’re saying that the author of this book is related to the Shi clan?”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Sazen nodded.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;In that case, she also understood why they avoided the censors. It must have been to protect their identity,&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Since you are here, Sazen, it’s not strange that other people have escaped.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Above all, it was none other than the villainess herself who freely handed out money, blew up the gunpowder, and had the menservants escape from the fortress.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Moreover, was there any among the menservants producing gunpowder skilled enough in writing to pen this story?&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“More than anything, do they have a reason to go so far as to write this story and risk exposing their identity?” Maomao groaned as she pulled out the medicine box drawer. The stock for brown sugar was quite low. “You didn’t give Chou’u brown sugar as a snack, right?&amp;#8221;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“No way. He would sneak some from time to time, though.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;I knew it&lt;/em&gt;, Maomao closed the drawer.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“It’s no wonder he read this book so intently, then. There were other similar books, but he skimmed through those.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Maomao looked at the last page of the book. The author’s name was more common than Kan Junjie: Chou San. She doubted it was their real name.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;As it was handwritten, there was no print shop seal either.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;A thorough measure against censors, huh?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Any idea as to who the author could be?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“No idea. I think there were hundreds of people at that fortress.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“That’s true.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Anyway, if Chou’u does anything unusual, I’ll notify you immediately.”&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;“Thanks.” Maomao picked up the book and left the apothecary. After asking the madam where the book came from, she had to return to the dorms.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;If only I could get time off freely.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;Not getting that was the tough part about being a salaried worker.&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;hr class="wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity" /&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;sub&gt;T/N: The name Chou San is the Japanese reading for 张三 (Zhang San). Just like 李四 (Li Si) and 王五 (Wang Wu), these names are as generic as they get. Might as well be anonymous haha&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p class="has-text-align-right"&gt;(&lt;a href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-03-peach-blossom-bookstore/"&gt;Next Chapter&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/p&gt;    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;div id="jp-post-flair" class="sharedaddy sd-like-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"&gt;&lt;div class="robots-nocontent sd-block sd-social sd-social-official sd-sharing"&gt;&lt;h3 class="sd-title"&gt;Share this:&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="sd-content"&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li class="share-facebook"&gt;&lt;div class="fb-share-button" data-href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-02-the-story-of-the-villainess/" data-layout="button_count"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li class="share-end"&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class='sharedaddy sd-block sd-like jetpack-likes-widget-wrapper jetpack-likes-widget-unloaded' id='like-post-wrapper-130534757-5538-68ced38bc1db2' data-src='//widgets.wp.com/likes/index.html?ver=20250920#blog_id=130534757&amp;amp;post_id=5538&amp;amp;origin=shikarito.wordpress.com&amp;amp;obj_id=130534757-5538-68ced38bc1db2' data-name='like-post-frame-130534757-5538-68ced38bc1db2' data-title='Like or Reblog'&gt;&lt;div class='likes-widget-placeholder post-likes-widget-placeholder' style='height: 55px;'&gt;&lt;span class='button'&gt;&lt;span&gt;Like&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class='loading'&gt;Loading&amp;#8230;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;span class='sd-text-color'&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a class='sd-link-color' href="https://shikarito.wordpress.com/kusuriya-no-hitorigoto/15-02-the-story-of-the-villainess/"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/main&gt;</description>
